==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Litany
<hw>Lit"a*ny</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"⟦adot⟧*n⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Litanies</plw>
<pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"⟦adot⟧*n⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>letanie</ets>,
OF. <ets>letanie</ets>, F. <ets>litanie</ets>, L. <ets>litania</ets>,
Gr. <grk>litanei`a</grk>, fr. <grk>litaney`ein</grk> to pray, akin to
<grk>li`tesqai</grk>, <grk>li`ssesqai</grk>, to pray, <grk>lith`</grk>
prayer.]</ety> <def>A solemn form of supplication in the public worship
of various churches, in which the clergy and congregation join, the
former leading and the latter responding in alternate sentences. It is
usually of a penitential character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Supplications . . . for the appeasing of God's wrath were of the
Greek church termed <qex>litanies</qex>, and rogations of the Latin.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Litarge</ent>⟦br⟧
